{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:55:50.309Z","seq":1,"event":"user_message","data":{"role":"user","content":"Design a PostgreSQL schema (with migrations) for a geolocated weather app. Create tables for users (optional), saved locations, and a weather_cache table keyed by (lat, lon, units, range) with `expires_at` for TTL-based caching. Add indexes for fast lookups by user_id and for fetching the latest non-expired cache entry."}}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:56:02.827Z","seq":2,"event":"tool_call","data":{"toolName":"mcp__agentloop__delegate_work","toolUseId":"call_SpuGlG3GwABQyrGLN5GrSnnK","input":{"title":"Design PostgreSQL schema and migrations for geolocated weather app caching","description":"Implement a PostgreSQL schema (with migrations) for a geolocated weather app.\n\nRequirements:\n1) Create core tables:\n- users table (optional for app flow, but include schema support)\n- saved_locations table linked to users for user-saved places\n- weather_cache table keyed by (lat, lon, units, range)\n\n2) weather_cache behavior:\n- Support TTL-based caching via expires_at timestamp\n- Ensure cache retrieval can efficiently fetch the latest non-expired entry for a given (lat, lon, units, range)\n\n3) Indexing requirements:\n- Add indexes for fast lookups by user_id (especially saved_locations)\n- Add indexes optimized for cache reads of latest non-expired record\n\n4) Migration requirements:\n- Provide forward migration(s) to create tables, constraints, and indexes\n- Provide rollback/down migration(s)\n- Include reasonable data types and constraints (e.g., coordinate precision/ranges, not-null where appropriate)\n\n5) Acceptance criteria:\n- Migrations run cleanly up/down on PostgreSQL\n- Composite key strategy for weather_cache is explicit and enforces intended uniqueness/versioning behavior\n- Query pattern for 'latest non-expired cache entry' is performant and index-backed\n- Schema is documented briefly in migration comments or README note\n\nPlease decompose this into implementable tasks with dependencies, assign engineer + QA steps, and execute.","priority":"high","agentHint":"product-manager"}}}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:56:02.866Z","seq":3,"event":"user_message","data":{"role":"user","content":"Build a FastAPI backend using the Postgres schema. Integrate OpenWeatherMap (https://openweathermap.org/api) to fetch current weather and forecasts (1 day, 3 days, 7 days), and implement a read-through cache in Postgres to reduce API calls. Add an endpoint to auto-detect approximate user location via `https://ipapi.co/json/`, plus endpoints for saved locations CRUD and for retrieving forecasts by coordinates."}}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:56:17.655Z","seq":4,"event":"tool_call","data":{"toolName":"mcp__agentloop__delegate_work","toolUseId":"call_kfq0Yukd7E09bciuRJjOIZBC","input":{"title":"FastAPI weather backend with Postgres cache, location detection, and saved locations CRUD","description":"Build a production-ready FastAPI backend using the existing Postgres schema. Integrate OpenWeatherMap APIs to fetch current weather and forecasts for 1-day, 3-day, and 7-day horizons. Implement a read-through cache stored in Postgres to reduce third-party API calls and enforce TTL-based freshness. Add endpoint for approximate user location detection via https://ipapi.co/json/. Add endpoints for saved locations CRUD and endpoint(s) to retrieve forecast by coordinates. Include robust validation, error handling, retries/timeouts for external APIs, and clear API contracts.\n\nRequirements and acceptance criteria:\n1) Data/API integration\n- Use OpenWeatherMap API key from environment config.\n- Support current weather plus forecast responses mapped to 1d, 3d, 7d views.\n- Normalize OpenWeatherMap response payloads into backend response models.\n\n2) Read-through cache in Postgres\n- Cache key includes latitude, longitude, forecast horizon/type, and units where applicable.\n- On request: return fresh cached data if valid; otherwise fetch from OpenWeatherMap, persist cache row, then return data.\n- Implement TTL strategy (configurable) and stale eviction/cleanup approach.\n- Ensure cache table/indexes support efficient lookups.\n\n3) Location detection endpoint\n- Add endpoint that calls https://ipapi.co/json/ and returns approximate city/region/country/lat/lon.\n- Handle upstream failures gracefully with meaningful status codes/messages.\n\n4) Saved locations CRUD\n- Create/list/get/update/delete saved locations.\n- Location model includes at least name/label + coordinates (+ optional metadata).\n- Validate coordinate ranges and required fields.\n\n5) Forecast by coordinates endpoint\n- Endpoint accepts lat/lon (and optional horizon/units) and returns weather from cache or provider.\n- Clearly indicate source metadata if useful (cache hit/miss timestamp).\n\n6) Non-functional\n- FastAPI routing structure, service layer separation, and DB access patterns consistent with project conventions.\n- Add tests (unit/integration as appropriate) for cache behavior, API endpoints, and external client mocking.\n- Update docs/README/env examples for required variables and endpoint usage.\n- QA validation includes functional endpoint checks and regression pass.\n\nPlease decompose into implementation tasks with dependencies and assign engineer/qa-tester appropriately.","priority":"high","agentHint":"product-manager"}}}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:56:17.721Z","seq":5,"event":"user_message","data":{"role":"user","content":"Build a Svelte frontend that calls the FastAPI backend. Create a simple UI that lets the user type a location or auto-detect it, then displays today, next 3 days, and week forecasts with loading and error states. Include a saved locations dropdown (if available) and unit switching (metric/imperial)."}}
{"timestamp":"2026-03-05T12:56:33.512Z","seq":6,"event":"tool_call","data":{"toolName":"mcp__agentloop__delegate_work","toolUseId":"call_sLzqQGTOwcYB8ycVgpM6zGY7","input":{"title":"Build Svelte weather frontend integrated with FastAPI backend","description":"Create implementation tasks to build a Svelte frontend that integrates with the existing FastAPI weather backend. Scope:\n- Build a simple, responsive UI where users can either type a location or auto-detect their current location.\n- Fetch and display forecasts for: today, next 3 days, and weekly forecast.\n- Include clear loading states for each fetch flow and user-friendly error states (network/API/location permission errors).\n- Include saved locations dropdown if backend exposes saved locations; gracefully hide/disable this section if unavailable.\n- Include unit switching between metric and imperial and ensure forecast values update consistently.\n- Wire API calls to FastAPI endpoints with proper request/response handling and environment-configurable base URL.\n- Add basic tests (component and/or integration where applicable) and QA validation criteria.\nAcceptance criteria should include:\n1) User can search by location and receive all three forecast views.\n2) User can auto-detect location (with permission flow handling).\n3) Unit toggle updates displayed temperatures/wind units correctly.\n4) Saved locations dropdown appears when data exists and selection triggers forecast refresh.\n5) Loading and error states are visible and recoverable.\n6) Frontend passes build/lint/type checks and smoke test against FastAPI backend.","priority":"high","agentHint":"product-manager"}}}
